2026-04-21 01:30:13 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['cable pair between power supply module and control module (one conductor open or not actually connected)', 'internal series wiring from control‑module input terminals to the switch and onward to the control‑module output terminals (open circuit)'] hypothesis_explanation='The observations show: (1) The power‑supply green LED is on, so 12 V is present at the power‑supply module. (2) The red inverted‑cables LED on the control module is ON in all tested polarities between modules. In this design that LED is wired between the 12 V line and the 0 V line but oriented so that it conducts only when these two lines are reversed somewhere between the power supply and the control module. (3) Swapping polarity of the cables between power supply and control module causes no change: the red LED remains lit and the load remains fully off. (4) Swapping polarity between control module and load module also has no effect: the red LED stays lit and neither the main nor the internal lamp ever receives power.\n\nFrom (3) and (4) we know the control module always “sees” a condition equivalent to reversed or abnormal supply regardless of cable polarity, and the load never sees any usable 12 V in any orientation. If the problem were only at the load module (e.g., the diode or lamps open), the red LED behavior would still depend on actual polarity from the supply and would change when the first cable pair was swapped. The fact that it does not change indicates that the fault lies between the power‑supply output terminals and the internal control‑module wiring up to and including the switch/output path.\n\nThe most consistent fault is an open or miswired connection on one of the conductors between the power supply and control module, or an internal open in the control module’s series path (e.g., open trace, failed switch contact, or broken solder joint) such that the 12 V and 0 V lines are not forming a proper through path to the module’s output. In that case, the red LED\x00A0can still be referenced to an internal node and appear lit as if polarity were wrong, while no current reaches the load regardless of any polarity swapping. Therefore the suspected faulty elements are the cable pair between the power supply and the control module (one conductor open / not actually connected) and/or the internal series wiring from the control‑module input terminals through the switch to its output terminals.'
